While not required for this course, you will find many resources online which make code sharing very easy with OpenCV, and it even provides an alternative to installing on your own system if you have struggles, using a remote instance."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Test the install","timeRequired":"PT3M"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Get started with OpenCV and Python","timeRequired":"PT5M36S","description":"This chapter will focus on the core image manipulation concepts and operations. This video will show how to open images, view them using the built-in Python and OpenCV tools, then save images back to disk. If you are using Google Collab, you should skip to the next video."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Get started with OpenCV and Python: Google Collab","timeRequired":"PT6M5S","description":"This module is for Google Collab users and how to follow future videos in this course. This video will also show how to load images into Collab, view them using matplotlib, then save images back to the environment, where they can be downloaded locally."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Access and understand pixel data","timeRequired":"PT4M12S","description":"This module will introduce the fundamentals of accessing the information contained within an image. Sometimes it can be difficult to visualize data structures, but it is particularly important for computer vision applications to stay aware of what data you are accessing and keep track of data types. Patrick also exposes some of the initial uses of NumPy for efficient matrix processing."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Data types and structures","timeRequired":"PT7M36S","description":"Patrick introduces the most commonly used data formats with image processing, and how to use the NumPy library to generate uniform-colored images. It is important to stay aware of what data types variables are at all times as functions only expect certain kinds, and often there are performance impacts of storing unnecessary image variables."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Image types and color channels","timeRequired":"PT8M51S","description":"Images come in various file formats and color profiles. It is important to understand the color space you are working in, and in many cases, it will be useful to transform from one space to another—such as from full color to black and white and from BGR to other formats like HSV. This module will show how to check and modify image color profiles."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Pixel manipulations and filtering","timeRequired":"PT4M41S","description":"Learn more about working with image channels and color spaces, and about efficient traversing through matrices."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Blur, dilation, and erosion","timeRequired":"PT5M50S","description":"There are a number of fundamental, basic filters key to general image processing. After learning about the concept of a filter template and its use, you will learn how to utilize the blur, dilation, and erosion filters in OpenCV. These filters have many use cases, often used as preprocessors to additional more advanced image processing or manipulation."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Scale and rotate images","timeRequired":"PT5M14S","description":"Learn these fundamental image operations, which are key tools in many image-processing scenarios. Patrick will briefly cover the high-level mathematics behind these transformations, which can assist with understanding limitations and artifacts that can result. The key is to remember images are essentially matrices and vice versa."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Use video inputs","timeRequired":"PT4M57S","description":"OpenCV provides easy access to video feeds, enabling applications to provide real-time processing and can even display the processed video output. In a real-time application, the video feed is tapped for an image at the start of a repeating loop which represents the actual image processing to occur. If having trouble accessing a live video stream, raw image sequence files are available for any future modules utilizing live video feeds."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Create custom interfaces","timeRequired":"PT4M50S","description":"Patrick shows how to leverage basic image manipulation and live video feeds to create customized real-time interfaces. Even for non-video applications, it can be useful to test a system using video feeds to test a program's robustness and corner cases by testing various image inputs by way of an image sequence or live video feed."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Create a simple drawing app","timeRequired":"PT2M15S","description":"In this challenge, create a simple drawing application that allows you to paint circles onto a white canvas. It must also be able to switch colors with some kind of toggle."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Create a simple drawing app","timeRequired":"PT7M32S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Segmentation and binary images","timeRequired":"PT1M38S","description":"Binary images are a key component of many image-processing algorithms. These pure, nonaliased, black-and-white images are the result of extracting out the desired pieces of an image for further processing. After creating a binary image from the source, you can do a lot when it comes to image processing. Learn to use and apply the dilate and erode functions as an additional filtering technique."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Simple thresholding","timeRequired":"PT6M34S","description":"Binary images are a key component of many image-processing algorithms. These pure, nonaliased, black-and-white images are the result of extracting out the desired pieces of an image for further processing. After creating a binary image from the source, you can do a lot when it comes to image processing. Learn to use and apply the dilate and erode functions as an additional filtering technique."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Adaptive thresholding","timeRequired":"PT4M38S","description":"While simple thresholding has its limits, adaptive thresholding techniques can increase the versatility of image thresholding operations. Instead of taking a simple global value as a threshold comparison, adaptive thresholding will look at the local neighborhood of the image to determine whether a relative threshold is met. In this way, it is possible to counteract issues such as uneven lighting."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Skin detection","timeRequired":"PT6M31S","description":"Basic skin detection can be accomplished through channel-based filtering. This method of detection is relatively simple, though requires some adjustments based on scene light and camera calibration. This quick and dirty method can allow you to perform simple skin detection for other applications like recognizing hand gestures or shapes."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Introduction to contours","timeRequired":"PT1M38S","description":"In this module, Patrick introduces the concept of contours. A single contour can be thought of as a point-to-point path that forms a closed, non-intersecting border around a single object. The OpenCV contours algorithm will generate a list of individual contours for all non-touching objects in an image."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Contour object detection","timeRequired":"PT6M56S","description":"Having explained how contours work, Patrick now shows how to generate and display contours found in an image. This function call will generate all the contours in an image and draw these outlines onto a displayed image, and even allow you to fill the areas. There are some additional settings and certain preprocessing you can do to improve or adjust the desired output of contours."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Area, perimeter, center, and curvature","timeRequired":"PT8M19S","description":"There are additional ways to characterize objects in images, including by measuring the curviness of an object's outline and the area contained by a contour loop. Some of these parameters are obtained by leveraging the contour, closed-loop data. Patrick shows how to determine these attributes to characterize multiple objects within a single image for comparison."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Canny edge detection","timeRequired":"PT8M1S","description":"Canny edge detection is a useful algorithm commonly used as a pre-processor for finding contours and other object detection methods. It works by finding and accentuating the edges within an image. The result can be drawn into a binary image with multiple continuous line sets. While these lines define edges and not necessarily enclosed areas, it happens to still be a useful pre-processor to then run contours against the output of canny edges."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Object detection overview","timeRequired":"PT1M59S","description":"While this course only covers a few basic ways to identify and characterize image objects, there are many other applications and advanced techniques as well as applications for objects identified in an image or sequence. Patrick briefly covers some of the other capabilities with OpenCV for more advanced applications such as optical flow and object tracking."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Assign object ID and attributes","timeRequired":"PT50S","description":"Using the skills of this chapter, segment and identify all of the objects in the provided reference file. Assign each detected object a unique color and fill its area on a black background. Additionally, for each color ID, print out the following properties: area, perimeter length, object center, and curvature."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Assign object ID and attributes","timeRequired":"PT10M5S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Overview of face and feature detection","timeRequired":"PT1M14S","description":"This chapter provides an overview of different approaches to detecting features, including the classic case of detecting faces. In image processing, features are any kind of the point of interest within an image. They are often recognizable, \"salient\" components ideally are invariant to transformations such as rotation or scaling. For example, the area of a circle may not be a feature, but the invariant shape itself might be. Detecting features is a crux for most image processing techniques."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Introduction to template matching","timeRequired":"PT2M19S","description":"Template matching is a method of searching for a similar pattern between pictures. This is accomplished by taking a reference image, and sliding it around another comparison image while taking differences at each position. The result of these differences indicates how close a particular area of the comparing image matches the template."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Application of template matching","timeRequired":"PT5M19S","description":"Understanding how template matching works, the use case is applied to detecting faces in an image. Using the provided template face image in the provided files, this module shows how to use the algorithm to detect faces in either provided images or even in a live video feed. Patrick explains some of the limitations and workarounds of template matching, including the effect of scaling or rotation compared to a source template object."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Haar cascading","timeRequired":"PT2M30S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Face detection","timeRequired":"PT5M25S","description":"Given the limitations of template matching on orientation and lighting, other methods of face detection have developed over time. This module covers the use of another machine learning-based face detection algorithm available with OpenCV. Explore how to use the faceCascade method to determine if a particular area of an image is a face or not."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Eye detection","timeRequired":"PT59S","description":"This challenge is to take the previous method of Haar cascading and apply it to detect and draw circles around eyes found in an image. Understanding this will allow you to grasp the more complex topics to follow in this course."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Multiclass deep neural networks","timeRequired":"PT3M4S","description":"This video generalizes two-class problems to multiclass problems and neural layers with a single hidden layer to deep neural networks with multiple layers that can handle highly non-linear problems. These two generalizations are particularly important because most real-world tasks, such as machine translation, speech recognition, and image classification are highly nonlinear multiclass problems."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"What is a convolutional filter?","timeRequired":"PT3M58S","description":"This video will explain how convolutional filters extract features with a small number of parameters using image processing as a motivating example. Understanding convolution is important because it is the basis of numerous deep neural networks for image and text processing."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Deep convolutional neural networks","timeRequired":"PT3M30S","description":"This video describes how multiple layers of convolution filters are put together to form very powerful deep neural networks for image processing problems. This is important to understand the impact of many deep convolutional neural networks (CNNs) such as AlexNet, VGGNet, and InceptionNet."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Transfer learning","timeRequired":"PT3M46S","description":"This video will discuss how deep neural networks that are trained on a large amount of data sourced from multiple domains can be used to improve the accuracy of targeted tasks. Transfer learning and fine-tuning are the sources of state-of-the-art results in applications such as NLP and image processing."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Modeling sequences with language models","timeRequired":"PT3M31S","description":"This video describes how temporal structure in neural networks is used in modeling sequence data like text, video, and speech. Understanding sequential modeling is a must for appreciating the widespread application of deep neural nets in domains like speech recognition, video processing, and natural language processing (NLP)."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Recurrent neural network language models","timeRequired":"PT3M43S","description":"This video will explain the concept of recurrent connections or self-loops in neural networks. These recurrent connections are what enable a neural network to remember temporal history, and thus properly model sequential data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Machine translation and encoder-decoder networks","timeRequired":"PT5M35S","description":"This video motivates and explains encoder-decoder neural networks in the context of machine translation. Encoder-decoder neural networks are important because they are now used in a variety of diverse applications such as translation, speech recognition, and image and video captioning."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Attention-based neural networks","timeRequired":"PT6M2S","description":"This video will describe how attention mechanisms enable neural networks to focus on specific patterns. Attention enables focused, and therefore, more powerful modeling, and is widely used in today's neural network models."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Transformer model","timeRequired":"PT4M","description":"This video will describe transformer architecture, a specific type of neural architecture that makes heavy use of attention both from the left and the right of the input under consideration. Transformers have gained huge popularity since their introduction in 2017, and are now widely used in NLP and image and video modeling as well."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Pretrained language models","timeRequired":"PT5M39S","description":"This video will describe the BERT model, which is a large language model based on the transformer architecture, pretrained on a large corpus of available data, and then fine-tuned for specific target tasks. BERT, which was introduced in 2018, is now a mainstay in NLP modeling and has also made its way into image and video modeling."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Motivation and introduction","timeRequired":"PT4M15S","description":"This video will explain that you need different kinds of deep neural networks for graphs because the deep neural networks in previous chapters are designed for grid data or sequence data. Understanding graphs with deep neural networks are important because many AI application tasks are done on top of social graphs or knowledge graphs."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Node embeddings","timeRequired":"PT5M27S","description":"This video describes node embedding methods, a class of methods with a simple neural network to learn embedding—latent vector—for each node in the graph. These methods generate an embedding vector for each node, which can be used as node features in other AI tasks."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Graph neural networks","timeRequired":"PT5M7S","description":"This video will present Graph neural networks (GNN) that apply deep neural networks to a local neighborhood of a given node to make a prediction for the node. After watching this video, you will be able to tell whether a neural network is the best choice out of a few classifiers in machine learning for a specific problem."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Types of neural networks","timeRequired":"PT2M38S","description":"Neural networks aren't only used for classification: as the name suggests, neural networks were inspired by the structure of the human brain, and so, they can be used to classify things, make predictions, suggest actions, discover patterns, and much more. After watching this video, you will be able to add different types of neural networks to your toolbox for solving problems other than classification."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Multilayer perceptrons","timeRequired":"PT1M44S","description":"Since there are many types of neural networks and models of the brain, we'll zero in on the type of neural network we'll use in this course—the multilayer perceptron. After watching this video, you will be able to design a multilayer perceptron graphically from a set of parameters like the number of inputs, outputs, and layers."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Neurons and the brain","timeRequired":"PT1M49S","description":"The inspiration for artificial neural networks is the brain, which is the ultimate network of neurons. After watching this video, you will be able to relate parts of a biological neuron to C++ elements, which will allow you to make a model of the brain. This model is the neural network you will create throughout the course to complete the final project."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"A simple model of a neuron","timeRequired":"PT5M43S","description":"The fact that neurons seem to fire as a result of the stimulus in their inputs is a behavior that may be implemented by many mathematical models. After watching this video, you will be able to create a very simple model for a neuron based on a weighted sum. This will be your first approach to making a model of the brain, which you'll gradually refine into your neural network."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Activation functions","timeRequired":"PT6M21S","description":"One of the shortcomings of your basic neuron is that different neurons produce results of different sizes, which is a problem when comparing something very small with something very large. Think of it as comparing a grain of sand with a planet. After watching this video, you will be able to choose from a variety of activation functions to solve this problem."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Perceptrons: A better model of a neuron","timeRequired":"PT6M32S","description":"Now that you know how to make a weighted sum and how an activation function can help constrain the results in a specified range, it's time to put these two together. After watching this video, you will be able to create the final building block of our neural network—a neuron model known as a perceptron."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Finish the perceptron","timeRequired":"PT1M7S","description":"It's time for a challenge. You will finish the perceptron code with the Sigmoid activation function."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Finish the perceptron","timeRequired":"PT46S","description":"This video will demonstrate a possible solution for the perceptron you'll use in the remainder of the course."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Logic gates","timeRequired":"PT3M54S","description":"Perceptrons are capable of performing logical operations. That is to say, they can behave as logic gates. After watching this video, you will be able to tap into the weights of your single-layer perceptron to make it behave like an AND gate."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Logic gates with perceptrons","timeRequired":"PT1M","description":"Time for another challenge. You will use the knowledge you've obtained so far to come up with the weights to make your perceptron behave like an OR gate."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Logic gates with perceptrons","timeRequired":"PT1M6S","description":"This video will demonstrate a solution for the OR gate challenge."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Linear separability","timeRequired":"PT3M28S","description":"A big complication that got scientists stuck in the 1970s was getting a perceptron to learn the behavior of an XOR gate. After watching this video, you will be able to create a neural network that does behave as an XOR gate by using three perceptrons and some logic."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Writing the multilayer perceptron class","timeRequired":"PT3M46S","description":"Interconnecting perceptrons enable the network to classify data with non-linearly separable classes. After watching this video, you will be able to interconnect perceptrons to create a neural network model called a multilayer perceptron (MLP)."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Finish the multilayer perceptron class","timeRequired":"PT1M58S","description":"It's time for another challenge. Your task will be to create a simple multilayer perceptron with three neurons. Optionally, you may write a flexible one with the number of inputs, layers, and outputs as parameters."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Finish the multilayer perceptron class","timeRequired":"PT2M36S","description":"This video will demonstrate a solution to the multilayer perceptron challenge."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"The need for training","timeRequired":"PT4M45S","description":"Up to this point, you've inserted the behavior into the neurons by entering their weights. So where is the intelligence in a neural network? After watching this video, you will be able to understand why neural networks require training, and why they'd be useless if they weren't able to learn."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"The training process","timeRequired":"PT3M47S","description":"Neural networks are useful because of their ability to learn. After watching this video, you will be able to employ a widely accepted high-level procedure to train a neural network using several data sets."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Error function","timeRequired":"PT2M27S","description":"As the name suggests, an error function measures how badly a classifier is doing, which is essential in the training process. After watching this video, you will be able to create an error function for your multilayer perceptron."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Gradient descent","timeRequired":"PT2M53S","description":"Gradient descent is a technique that consists of modifying the weights of a network in the direction that reduces the error value in the most significant measure. After watching this video, you will be ready to learn how to implement a training algorithm."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"The delta rule","timeRequired":"PT3M34S","description":"Now that you've created an error function, the next step is to train your neural network using gradient descent so that it can classify data from the samples you feed it. After watching this video, you will be able to train a single-layer perceptron by using an algorithm known as the delta rule."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"The backpropagation algorithm","timeRequired":"PT9M12S","description":"Now that you have trained a single-layer perceptron, it's time to move on to training multilayer perceptrons. Unlike the delta rule, the backpropagation algorithm adjusts the weights of all the layers in the network. After watching this video, you will be able to implement the backpropagation algorithm to train multilayer perceptrons, the missing piece in your neural network."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Write your own backpropagation function","timeRequired":"PT3M29S","description":"It's time to write some code again. In this challenge, you will have to create a function that runs one iteration of the backpropagation algorithm."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Write your own backpropagation function","timeRequired":"PT5M","description":"This video will demonstrate a solution to this challenge. It is great that, should the viewer choose to follow along or download the code, they will be left with a very general neural network Python class that they can use to continue exploring NN and ML applications. I often found the practical challenges tricky, at least in part because of the abrupt introduction of new concepts and particular way of solving them - something everyone should do following this course is go through the functions for themselves and re-write them more efficiently (if possible) and/or in a way that makes more sense to them. The \"segment display recognition\" exercises and demonstrations at the end are quite illuminating, and even more visualizations can be made on one's own (such as tracking the evolution of one-hot outputs for a given input) to visualize an even greater variety of NN behaviors!
